    <h4>Getting Started</h4>
    <p>Click <strong>Open File</strong> to load an Excel spreadsheet (.xlsx) or CSV file.
    Select a chart type from the left sidebar, configure options in the right panel,
    then click <strong>Generate Plot</strong>.</p>

    <h4>Excel Layout</h4>
    <p>For bar, box, and violin charts, use a <strong>flat header</strong> layout:
    Row 1 = group names, Rows 2+ = numeric values. Each column is one group.</p>
    <p>For line and scatter charts, Column 1 = X values, Column 2+ = Y replicates.
    Row 1 contains the X-axis label and series names.</p>

    <h4>Statistical Tests</h4>
    <p><strong>Parametric</strong> (default): Uses ANOVA + Tukey HSD for 3+ groups,
    Welch's t-test for 2 groups. Assumes normally distributed data.</p>
    <p><strong>Non-parametric</strong>: Uses Kruskal-Wallis + Dunn's post-hoc.
    Appropriate for non-normal data or ordinal scales.</p>
    <p><strong>Paired</strong>: Uses paired t-test or Wilcoxon signed-rank.
    Requires equal group sizes (matched subjects).</p>

    <h4>Multiple Comparison Corrections</h4>
    <p><code>Holm-Bonferroni</code> (recommended): step-down procedure, controls FWER.</p>
    <p><code>Bonferroni</code>: most conservative. <code>BH (FDR)</code>: controls
    false discovery rate — more liberal.</p>

    <h4>Effect Sizes</h4>
    <p><strong>Cohen's d</strong>: standardized mean difference.
    d &lt; 0.2 = negligible, 0.2–0.5 = small, 0.5–0.8 = medium, &gt; 0.8 = large.</p>
    <p><strong>Hedges' g</strong>: bias-corrected version of Cohen's d for small samples.</p>

    <h4>Keyboard Shortcuts</h4>
    <p><code>⌘1–9</code> Switch chart type &nbsp; <code>⌘Z</code> Undo &nbsp;
    <code>⌘⇧Z</code> Redo &nbsp; <code>⌘E</code> Export</p>
